WEBVTT

00:11.078 --> 00:13.647
[eerie music] ‐ Very particular
how they were arranged.

00:13.680 --> 00:15.482
It was intentional.

00:15.516 --> 00:19.086
‐ Percy's mother left her
when she was a baby.

00:19.119 --> 00:20.654
I raised her as my own.

00:20.687 --> 00:23.290
‐ So you don't think that she
jumped off the cliff anymore?

00:23.323 --> 00:25.225
‐ I don't know what to think.

00:25.259 --> 00:27.094
Somebody has a hold on her.

00:27.127 --> 00:29.129
‐ He swears he saw
Percy drive by

00:29.162 --> 00:30.397
in her car last night

00:30.430 --> 00:32.633
about a half hour
after your 911 call.

00:32.666 --> 00:33.800
‐ After?

00:33.834 --> 00:35.602
‐ The car dies, she's stuck.

00:35.636 --> 00:38.405
‐ And is never heard from
again.

00:38.438 --> 00:39.540
You know this guy?

00:39.573 --> 00:40.641
‐ Probably seen him around.

00:40.674 --> 00:43.443
‐ You never told me that
she left the island last year.

00:43.477 --> 00:45.646
‐ Why aren't we talking
about CJ Lam?

00:45.679 --> 00:47.014
‐ Hey.

00:47.047 --> 00:48.148
[heavy thud]

00:48.182 --> 00:49.216
‐ He hurt Percy.
‐ Oh, my God.

00:49.249 --> 00:52.252
‐ That cut on her head?
I saw it with my own eyes.

00:52.286 --> 00:53.654
‐ How would she know
about a cut

00:53.687 --> 00:55.155
two hours later at the bar?

00:55.189 --> 00:57.090
‐ I didn't tell
anybody about that.

00:57.124 --> 00:58.458
‐ She's lying.

01:02.095 --> 01:05.065
[dramatic music]

01:05.098 --> 01:12.139
♪ ♪

01:24.218 --> 01:27.321
[suspenseful music]

01:27.354 --> 01:34.328
♪ ♪

01:42.503 --> 01:43.704
[engine starts]

02:29.149 --> 02:31.084
‐ Hi, you've reached
Sonya Barzel.

02:31.118 --> 02:33.587
Please leave a message.
Thanks.

02:33.620 --> 02:36.190
‐ Yeah, I might have a lead.

02:36.223 --> 02:38.492
Not sure I'll make it back
for the bird‐watching session.

02:38.525 --> 02:40.494
I'll let you know.

04:09.049 --> 04:10.150
[doorbell rings]

04:13.787 --> 04:15.556
‐ Good afternoon.

04:15.589 --> 04:17.624
‐ I'm sorry.
Can I help you?

04:17.658 --> 04:20.527
‐ I'm Harry Ambrose.
I'm part of an investigation

04:20.561 --> 04:23.263
involving a woman from Hanover.

04:23.297 --> 04:26.500
She's been missing
since Saturday.

04:26.533 --> 04:29.536
Percy Muldoon.

04:29.570 --> 04:31.471
‐ Are you police?

04:31.505 --> 04:33.073
‐ I retired last year,

04:33.106 --> 04:35.642
but this is kind of a
all‐hands‐on‐deck situation.

04:35.676 --> 04:37.377
‐ I'm sorry, I‐‐

04:37.411 --> 04:38.478
I don't have time
for this right now.

04:38.512 --> 04:40.647
‐ Look, I did just see you

04:40.681 --> 04:42.983
talking with Meg Muldoon.

04:45.219 --> 04:48.589
‐ I'm sorry, but whatever
you're looking for,

04:48.622 --> 04:50.257
you're not gonna
find it in here.

04:50.290 --> 04:52.659
‐ You know,

04:52.693 --> 04:54.328
a lot of people
are worried about

04:54.361 --> 04:57.497
what might've happened to her.

04:57.531 --> 04:59.499
Can you at least tell me

04:59.533 --> 05:01.168
why Meg was here?

05:04.171 --> 05:07.708
‐ [sighs]
I'm Percy's mother.

05:11.545 --> 05:13.747
‐ Okay.

05:13.780 --> 05:15.649
‐ You saw her?

05:15.682 --> 05:18.785
‐ Ah, it's still not clear

05:18.819 --> 05:22.289
what happened exactly.

05:22.322 --> 05:25.659
Have you been in touch
over the years?

05:25.692 --> 05:28.195
‐ Yeah.

05:28.228 --> 05:30.330
They make me out to be
some sort of...

05:30.364 --> 05:34.067
deadbeat mother or something?

05:34.101 --> 05:36.003
‐ They said you weren't
around much.

05:36.036 --> 05:38.238
‐ [scoffs]

05:38.272 --> 05:41.508
‐ So, you and Sean‐‐
how'd you meet?

05:41.542 --> 05:43.610
‐ It was the summer
before senior year.

05:43.644 --> 05:45.145
I got a job waitressing,

05:45.179 --> 05:48.215
and Sean was just
a summer fling,

05:48.248 --> 05:50.017
and I got pregnant with Percy.

05:50.050 --> 05:53.787
And that was
the beginning of the end.

05:53.820 --> 05:56.623
‐ So you left?

05:56.657 --> 06:00.594
‐ You have to understand,
I was only 16 at the time,

06:00.627 --> 06:02.462
and nothing I could do
was ever good enough

06:02.496 --> 06:04.264
for Meg Muldoon.

06:05.399 --> 06:10.637
‐ [grunts]
You left without your baby.

06:10.671 --> 06:12.406
‐ After about a year,

06:12.439 --> 06:15.542
and I came back here
to finish school,

06:15.576 --> 06:19.112
and then, time passed,

06:19.146 --> 06:21.148
I met someone, got married,

06:21.181 --> 06:23.016
had a kid, bought a house,

06:23.050 --> 06:25.586
had two more,
bought a bigger house.

06:25.619 --> 06:29.389
I guess it just got easier

06:29.423 --> 06:32.059
to focus on the family
that wanted me.

06:32.092 --> 06:35.062
[melancholy music]

06:35.095 --> 06:38.799
Do you think she's in danger?

06:38.832 --> 06:41.001
‐ Yes.

06:41.034 --> 06:42.636
Looking more and more possible.

06:42.669 --> 06:45.639
♪ ♪

06:45.672 --> 06:48.075
With Meg today,
what was that about?

06:48.108 --> 06:51.345
‐ Uh, she just wanted to know
if I'd seen Percy.

06:51.378 --> 06:52.513
‐ And you told her what?

06:52.546 --> 06:55.649
‐ I told her that maybe instead
of barging into my home,

06:55.682 --> 06:59.019
she should try
looking into her own.

06:59.052 --> 07:01.288
‐ What do you mean by that?

07:01.321 --> 07:06.193
‐ Oh, you don't know
Meg Muldoon,

07:06.226 --> 07:11.231
but you will soon, believe me.

07:11.265 --> 07:15.536
That woman is a tyrant.

07:15.569 --> 07:19.406
‐ So you think that Percy was
trying to get away from her?

07:19.439 --> 07:24.578
‐ She did once before.

07:24.611 --> 07:28.315
She came here nine months ago.

07:28.348 --> 07:30.150
‐ Who cares
what they're made of?

07:30.184 --> 07:31.585
I think they're yummy.

07:31.618 --> 07:34.555
‐ So if it isn't really meat,
how can it look it's bleeding?

07:34.588 --> 07:37.291
[doorbell rings]

07:41.562 --> 07:43.597
‐ Percy?

07:43.630 --> 07:46.266
‐ Hi.

07:46.300 --> 07:48.335
Sorry to show up
without calling.

07:48.368 --> 07:51.738
And I know, it's‐‐
it's been a minute.

07:51.772 --> 07:54.641
Um...

07:54.675 --> 07:57.711
I‐‐I just didn't know
where else to go.

07:59.613 --> 08:03.183
‐ Hey girls, this is Percy.

08:03.217 --> 08:05.786
Uh, she's a friend of mine.

08:05.819 --> 08:08.155
She's just gonna stay with us
for a little bit.

08:08.188 --> 08:12.759
‐ Hi.
It's, um... nice to meet you.

08:20.367 --> 08:22.736
‐ This is my son Paul's room.

08:22.769 --> 08:26.240
He is my oldest.

08:26.273 --> 08:29.776
My oldest with my husband Jory.

08:29.810 --> 08:31.311
He's away doing
freshman orientation

08:31.345 --> 08:32.546
at Bowdoin.

08:32.579 --> 08:35.549
So strange having him gone.

08:35.582 --> 08:38.652
‐ It must be tough.

08:38.685 --> 08:40.654
‐ Um, dinner's almost ready

08:40.687 --> 08:42.389
if you want to come down
and join us.

08:42.422 --> 08:47.094
‐ Oh, uh, it's okay.
I'm not hungry.

08:47.127 --> 08:48.662
‐ Okay, well,
I'll let you settle in.

08:48.695 --> 08:50.664
Bathroom's second door
on the right.

08:50.697 --> 08:52.199
And if you need anything,

08:52.232 --> 08:53.667
I'll just be down
in the kitchen.

08:53.700 --> 08:56.069
‐ Thanks.

08:56.103 --> 08:58.338
I appreciate it.

08:58.372 --> 09:00.641
‐ Yeah, of course.

09:00.674 --> 09:03.644
[ambient music]

09:03.677 --> 09:07.581
♪ ♪

09:07.614 --> 09:10.751
She had this big wad of cash.

09:10.784 --> 09:15.389
‐ You think she had
to flee the island fast?

09:15.422 --> 09:19.459
‐ I figured we'd talk about it
the next day, but...

09:19.493 --> 09:21.728
when I got up
the next morning, she was gone.

09:26.667 --> 09:29.269
[sniffles] I'm sorry.

09:29.303 --> 09:32.239
I wish I had more to tell you.

09:32.272 --> 09:36.410
I have a very busy day
ahead of me.

09:41.048 --> 09:43.217
‐ Uh, look,
I appreciate your time.

09:43.250 --> 09:46.453
And Percy needed somebody,

09:46.486 --> 09:48.655
she came to you.

09:48.689 --> 09:50.324
It's good you were there.

09:52.059 --> 09:54.494
‐ Uh, just‐‐

09:54.528 --> 09:56.330
she sent me this.

10:00.567 --> 10:03.003
[suspenseful music]

10:03.036 --> 10:08.208
It's only 20 minutes away,
but I never visited.

10:08.242 --> 10:11.545
Life just got in the way.

10:11.578 --> 10:13.447
‐ I understand.

10:29.663 --> 10:36.570
[eerie music] ♪ ♪

10:39.773 --> 10:42.209
‐ Honestly, I figured somebody
like you would probably show up

10:42.242 --> 10:45.746
at some point asking about her.

10:45.779 --> 10:49.283
‐ How long has it been
since she left?

10:49.316 --> 10:52.085
‐ About six months.

10:52.119 --> 10:54.054
She just peaced out.

10:54.087 --> 10:56.590
Um, fortunately, this place
is a pretty sweet deal,

10:56.623 --> 11:00.460
so found somebody
to take the room.

11:00.494 --> 11:02.563
‐ You and Percy
living together.

11:02.596 --> 11:03.430
How is that?

11:03.463 --> 11:06.433
Did you know each other
or something?

11:06.466 --> 11:08.569
‐ It was totally random.

11:08.602 --> 11:10.604
Craigslist.
‐ Hm.

11:10.637 --> 11:14.641
‐ And she seemed pretty cool,
so I thought, why not?

11:14.675 --> 11:19.079
‐ All right, I got you
your cookies,

11:19.112 --> 11:20.514
peanut butter,

11:20.547 --> 11:26.086
and...

11:26.119 --> 11:27.421
ta‐da.

11:27.454 --> 11:31.191
‐ Dude, I said fish sticks,

11:31.225 --> 11:33.026
like the‐‐
like the frozen things

11:33.060 --> 11:34.094
that you heat up in the oven.

11:34.127 --> 11:36.330
‐ This'll be so much better.

11:36.363 --> 11:40.767
Just you wait.
[viscera squelching]

11:40.801 --> 11:42.469
‐ Oh, my God.

11:42.503 --> 11:45.038
Oh, my God, what the fuck?

11:45.072 --> 11:46.240
Dude,

11:46.273 --> 11:49.209
where did you learn
how to do that?

11:49.243 --> 11:51.278
‐ Prison.

11:51.311 --> 11:54.281
‐ Wait, you're not serious.

11:54.314 --> 11:57.384
‐ Oh, my God, no.
[laughs]

11:57.417 --> 12:00.020
I learned it from my family.

12:00.053 --> 12:01.455
My‐‐my uncle, actually.

12:01.488 --> 12:03.090
‐ Okay, you do realize
I still have no clue

12:03.123 --> 12:04.658
where you're from, right?

12:04.691 --> 12:06.126
‐ I told you.

12:06.159 --> 12:08.295
Down east.

12:08.328 --> 12:10.330
Honestly,
I'm so sick of my family.

12:10.364 --> 12:15.469
I can‐‐can't even go there.

12:15.502 --> 12:17.337
‐ No, you can't wear that top.

12:17.371 --> 12:20.607
No, we cannot wear
the shirt to the club.

12:20.641 --> 12:22.709
‐ [laughs]

12:22.743 --> 12:24.678
‐ Do you not go clubbing
very often?

12:24.711 --> 12:27.014
‐ Uh, first time.

12:27.047 --> 12:28.715
‐ You innocent little virgin.

12:31.118 --> 12:34.788
‐ Hey, um, bad good idea or...

12:34.821 --> 12:37.491
good bad idea?

12:37.524 --> 12:39.660
‐ Let's not judge.
‐ [laughs]

12:39.693 --> 12:43.030
[hip‐hop music]

12:43.063 --> 12:45.232
‐ ♪ Baby, let's move it
to the rhythm ♪

12:45.265 --> 12:47.534
‐ And one, two.

12:47.568 --> 12:49.469
‐ ♪ Let me see you
walk out on the floor ♪

12:49.503 --> 12:51.305
Yeah!
‐ [laughs]

12:51.338 --> 12:52.606
Excuse me?

12:52.639 --> 12:54.608
I want to...

12:54.641 --> 12:57.778
‐ ♪ Let's break it down ♪

12:57.811 --> 12:59.413
‐ Hi.
‐ How are you?

12:59.446 --> 13:03.016
‐ ♪ Right here right now ♪

13:03.050 --> 13:04.551
‐ Okay.

13:04.585 --> 13:06.620
‐ ♪ Let me see you
shake that thing ♪

13:06.653 --> 13:10.190
♪ Hey, let me see you
shake that thing ♪

13:11.758 --> 13:14.728
[upbeat music]

13:14.761 --> 13:20.334
♪ ♪

13:20.367 --> 13:23.036
[both screaming]

13:23.070 --> 13:25.706
Okay, okay, but like if he‐‐

13:25.739 --> 13:27.641
if he hadn't had
that one missing tooth,

13:27.674 --> 13:30.744
he would've looked exactly
like Robert Pattinson.

13:30.777 --> 13:34.081
Tell me he wouldn't look
like Robert Pattinson.

13:34.114 --> 13:37.017
‐ Sort of.

13:37.050 --> 13:39.753
‐ Oh, it's freezing.

13:39.786 --> 13:42.789
‐ Do you ever feel
like you're cursed?

13:42.823 --> 13:46.727
‐ Like with men?
Uh, yeah.

13:46.760 --> 13:49.363
‐ No, I‐‐I mean more like

13:49.396 --> 13:52.099
no matter what you do, you‐‐

13:52.132 --> 13:54.301
you can't get away?

13:57.371 --> 14:03.510
‐ What‐‐we‐‐we should just
do this every weekend.

14:03.544 --> 14:07.247
‐ We really hit it off.
I got her a job

14:07.281 --> 14:10.684
at the clothing store
where I work,

14:10.717 --> 14:14.588
but after about a month,
things got like, really weird.

14:18.258 --> 14:21.228
[eerie music]

14:21.261 --> 14:25.766
♪ ♪

14:25.799 --> 14:27.301
‐ I'm not here, okay?

14:27.334 --> 14:29.036
If a man comes looking for me,
I'm not here.

14:29.069 --> 14:30.070
‐ What?

14:30.103 --> 14:32.206
‐ He can't know that I'm here.

14:32.239 --> 14:34.374
‐ Who can't know that you're‐‐
‐ Please!

14:51.124 --> 14:53.060
‐ Did she say who it was?

14:53.093 --> 14:54.628
‐ No, um,

14:54.661 --> 14:57.598
she was, like,
totally freaked out,

14:57.631 --> 14:59.633
and I couldn't
get her to calm down.

15:02.503 --> 15:04.071
‐ CJ Lam.

15:04.104 --> 15:08.075
Did she ever mention that guy?

15:08.108 --> 15:11.778
‐ That doesn't
sound familiar, no.

15:11.812 --> 15:15.215
After that, she just
started spiraling.

15:15.249 --> 15:17.084
She wouldn't leave the house.

15:17.117 --> 15:20.087
[eerie music]

15:20.120 --> 15:24.458
♪ ♪

15:24.491 --> 15:26.760
Percy?

15:26.793 --> 15:29.763
Percy.
‐ What?

15:37.070 --> 15:38.205
‐ Hey.

15:38.238 --> 15:40.641
Hey.

15:40.674 --> 15:42.576
It is Friday night.

15:42.609 --> 15:44.511
You have not been out in weeks.

15:44.545 --> 15:45.479
Let's go.

15:45.512 --> 15:47.514
‐ Yeah, I just
don't feel well.

15:47.548 --> 15:49.016
‐ [groans]

15:49.049 --> 15:51.285
Well, I have something

15:51.318 --> 15:53.453
that will help with that.

15:53.487 --> 15:54.655
Come on!

15:54.688 --> 15:56.089
I need a wing woman.

15:56.123 --> 15:59.126
[dance music playing]

15:59.159 --> 16:04.598
♪ ♪

16:04.631 --> 16:06.333
Am I good?

16:10.804 --> 16:12.639
Mm!

16:14.474 --> 16:17.311
‐ I just wanna thank you.
‐ Hmm?

16:17.344 --> 16:19.613
‐ For being so‐‐

16:19.646 --> 16:21.615
so nice to me.

16:21.648 --> 16:25.352
‐ [chuckles] Oh, girl,

16:25.385 --> 16:27.020
of course, come on.

16:27.054 --> 16:34.194
♪ ♪

16:41.635 --> 16:44.605
[eerie music]

16:44.638 --> 16:51.578
♪ ♪

17:32.586 --> 17:34.755
Percy?

17:34.788 --> 17:37.758
[somber music]

17:37.791 --> 17:44.331
♪ ♪

17:44.364 --> 17:45.632
That was it.

17:45.666 --> 17:48.202
She was gone.
I never saw her again.

17:48.235 --> 17:50.070
And I tried calling her phone,

17:50.103 --> 17:53.073
but it was always going
straight to voicemail,

17:53.106 --> 17:56.710
and eventually, I just...

17:56.743 --> 17:59.279
gave up.

17:59.313 --> 18:01.615
‐ Do you think there was
some sort of fight?

18:01.648 --> 18:05.085
She didn't want to leave,
but...

18:05.118 --> 18:07.688
someone made her?

18:07.721 --> 18:10.524
‐ I wondered that.

18:10.557 --> 18:13.594
It was like,

18:13.627 --> 18:16.430
there was
this other side of her,

18:16.463 --> 18:19.233
this dark side,

18:19.266 --> 18:22.202
and it just won't let her go.

18:22.236 --> 18:25.205
[unsettling music]

18:25.239 --> 18:32.312
♪ ♪

18:48.395 --> 18:50.330
[ferry horn blows]

19:02.075 --> 19:06.079
‐ [echoing] You've seen
too much now, haven't you?

19:06.113 --> 19:12.219
You're not going to stop.

19:12.252 --> 19:14.054
‐ [echoing]
If something happened to you,

19:14.087 --> 19:17.558
there's gotta be consequences.

19:17.591 --> 19:22.496
‐ Why is that
so important to you?

19:22.529 --> 19:25.332
‐ People come into the world,

19:25.365 --> 19:29.703
They just try to survive.

19:29.736 --> 19:34.208
World takes them out.

19:34.241 --> 19:39.079
Doesn't care.

19:39.112 --> 19:44.084
‐ You have to admit, though,

19:44.117 --> 19:46.019
sometimes
it's easier on everybody

19:46.053 --> 19:50.457
if you just disappear.

20:09.276 --> 20:14.481
[ambient music] ♪ ♪

20:14.515 --> 20:16.617
‐ Okay, look, I know
I missed your call.

20:16.650 --> 20:19.119
It's so freaking patchy,
the service around here.

20:19.152 --> 20:21.321
‐ It's out by where
Percy's car was.

20:21.355 --> 20:23.323
You should see for yourself.

20:23.357 --> 20:25.158
‐ Let's go.

20:41.241 --> 20:42.609
‐ All right.

20:42.643 --> 20:44.611
It's right in here.

20:44.645 --> 20:51.752
♪ ♪

20:58.358 --> 21:00.060
It's over here.

21:16.376 --> 21:19.346
‐ It's kinda like
the way Percy's objects were

21:19.379 --> 21:21.782
on the bluff.

21:21.815 --> 21:26.753
It has the same crescent thing.

21:26.787 --> 21:28.522
You know, I‐‐I don't know
if there's a connection,

21:28.555 --> 21:33.560
but do you know anything about,
what would you call it?

21:33.594 --> 21:35.395
Night swimming, I guess.

21:35.429 --> 21:37.497
‐ Night swimming?

21:37.531 --> 21:40.234
‐ Yeah, it's just,
a couple of nights ago,

21:40.267 --> 21:43.737
I saw three women in the water,

21:43.770 --> 21:48.709
in the dark, sort of moaning.

21:48.742 --> 21:51.612
‐ Well, we do have our share
of tree‐huggers out here.

21:51.645 --> 21:55.349
‐ No, it's guttural.

21:55.382 --> 21:58.519
It's kinda like a ceremony,

21:58.552 --> 22:01.488
ritual kinda thing,
you know what I mean?

22:01.522 --> 22:06.627
And I think this
is maybe something like that.

22:06.660 --> 22:10.197
‐ I wouldn't know
anything about that.

22:10.230 --> 22:12.666
Marj is always trying
to get me to meditate.

22:18.071 --> 22:19.206
‐ Hey.

22:19.239 --> 22:21.341
‐ Oh, hey.

22:21.375 --> 22:23.177
You missed Gretta.
‐ Oh.

22:23.210 --> 22:27.481
‐ She wanted to say hi.

22:27.514 --> 22:30.484
‐ So did you get
some good pictures today?

22:30.517 --> 22:32.219
‐ Oh, so many.

22:32.252 --> 22:36.290
The way the light
plays off the waves, unreal.

22:36.323 --> 22:38.625
What about you?
Did you make any progress?

22:38.659 --> 22:40.594
‐ Yeah, yeah.

22:40.627 --> 22:41.795
‐ What?

22:41.828 --> 22:45.499
‐ Well, Meg Muldoon's
been lying to me.

22:45.532 --> 22:48.335
Percy ran away from home
nine months ago.

22:48.368 --> 22:50.037
‐ Wow.

22:50.070 --> 22:50.938
Ran away?

22:50.971 --> 22:53.707
‐ Yeah, I'd‐‐I'd like
to go and talk to her.

22:53.740 --> 22:57.344
‐ What, now? We have the‐‐
what about the reservation?

22:57.377 --> 22:58.779
‐ Well, I thought
maybe we could stop by

22:58.812 --> 23:01.748
on the way to the restaurant.

23:01.782 --> 23:03.750
‐ You wanna confront her
with me there?

23:03.784 --> 23:06.553
‐ No, I just want
to feel her out,

23:06.587 --> 23:09.089
see if there's anything else
that she's lying about,

23:09.122 --> 23:13.360
and maybe you could help
put her at ease.

23:13.393 --> 23:14.661
‐ Oh, God.

23:14.695 --> 23:16.496
Harry, really?

23:16.530 --> 23:18.332
‐ Just‐‐just for a few minutes.

23:18.365 --> 23:20.033
You know, small talk probably.

23:20.067 --> 23:22.302
And then we'd go to dinner.

23:22.336 --> 23:25.038
‐ Hm.

23:25.072 --> 23:28.075
‐ If they did something
to Percy,

23:28.108 --> 23:32.479
they could probably
get away with it.

23:32.513 --> 23:37.084
You're in this with me, right?

23:37.117 --> 23:38.485
‐ Okay.

23:38.519 --> 23:41.355
[pensive music]

23:41.388 --> 23:48.562
♪ ♪

23:59.339 --> 24:00.607
‐ Hello.

24:00.641 --> 24:02.342
‐ Did you find something?

24:02.376 --> 24:04.745
‐ Right now,
there's nothing new,

24:04.778 --> 24:07.347
but we're working on it.
‐ Oh, God.

24:07.381 --> 24:09.750
Every time the phone rings

24:09.783 --> 24:12.619
or somebody knocks
on my door...

24:12.653 --> 24:14.521
‐ Well, we were just going by.

24:14.555 --> 24:17.057
Thought we'd stop in.
This is Sonya.

24:17.090 --> 24:19.393
‐ Hi.
It's so nice to meet you.

24:19.426 --> 24:22.062
This is a beautiful house.

24:22.095 --> 24:24.364
‐ Oh, thank you.

24:24.398 --> 24:28.602
‐ Harry told me a little
about your‐‐your granddaughter.

24:28.635 --> 24:32.206
I've been wishing you the best.

24:32.239 --> 24:34.208
‐ I really believe,
in times like these,

24:34.241 --> 24:35.742
in staying positive.

24:35.776 --> 24:38.345
‐ Oh, it's essential.

24:38.378 --> 24:41.648
‐ We were on our way to dinner
and wanted to check in.

24:41.682 --> 24:43.650
I had this feeling that

24:43.684 --> 24:47.154
something might've
come up today.

24:47.187 --> 24:50.190
‐ No, I've just been
calling people,

24:50.224 --> 24:55.395
trying to figure out
where she might be.

24:55.429 --> 24:58.298
Do you wanna come in?

24:58.332 --> 25:02.302
‐ Well, I‐‐I have
a couple questions about Percy.

25:02.336 --> 25:04.071
‐ We don't wanna intrude.

25:04.104 --> 25:05.639
‐ No, we're about
to have dinner,

25:05.672 --> 25:08.075
and Colin's over
with his girlfriend,

25:08.108 --> 25:10.611
and you're welcome to join us.

25:10.644 --> 25:12.112
‐ That is so kind of you,

25:12.145 --> 25:16.483
but we have
dinner reservations.

25:16.517 --> 25:19.086
‐ We could just call
and cancel.

25:19.119 --> 25:22.155
‐ I‐‐we don't want to impose.

25:22.189 --> 25:23.257
‐ No trouble at all.

25:23.290 --> 25:24.658
We've got plenty of food,

25:24.691 --> 25:28.395
and we can talk about Percy.

25:28.428 --> 25:29.663
‐ It'd be very helpful.

25:45.546 --> 25:49.183
‐ Thank you, Holy Father,
for helping us stay patient and keep our faith
as we search for Percy.

25:49.216 --> 25:51.251
We know that you
will keep her safe

25:51.285 --> 25:53.787
until she has returned home.

25:53.820 --> 25:55.489
together: Bless us, o, Lord,
and these, thy gifts,

25:55.522 --> 25:57.291
which we are about to receive
from thy bounty,

25:57.324 --> 26:00.360
through Christ our Lord. Amen.

26:00.394 --> 26:01.528
‐ Well, eat up.

26:01.562 --> 26:03.597
There's plenty more
in the kitchen.

26:05.399 --> 26:08.101
‐ That's a‐‐a beautiful boat.

26:08.135 --> 26:09.603
‐ Oh, that's Finnoula.

26:09.636 --> 26:12.406
That's the boat
Percy learned to fish on.

26:12.439 --> 26:16.376
‐ Ah.
It's a beautiful photo too.

26:16.410 --> 26:18.679
Did you take it?
‐ Oh, God, no.

26:18.712 --> 26:22.015
I don't have a creative bone
in my body,

26:22.049 --> 26:23.650
but I do like artists.

26:23.684 --> 26:26.286
I hear you're a painter.
‐ Yeah.

26:26.320 --> 26:27.588
Well, since
I've been on the island,

26:27.621 --> 26:28.689
I've been
photographing things‐‐

26:28.722 --> 26:31.258
[phone ringing]

26:34.695 --> 26:36.396
‐ I got it.

26:36.430 --> 26:39.533
[tense music]

26:40.300 --> 26:41.535
Hello.

26:41.568 --> 26:43.470
Yep.

26:43.504 --> 26:45.005
Mm‐hmm.

26:45.038 --> 26:46.607
Are you serious?
‐ Sean?

26:46.640 --> 26:48.609
‐ It's‐‐it's Lou.
It's not about Percy.

26:48.642 --> 26:50.310
‐ [sighs]

26:50.344 --> 26:54.715
♪ ♪

26:54.748 --> 26:58.018
Sean, what's he going on about?

26:58.051 --> 26:59.686
Sean!

26:59.720 --> 27:01.588
‐ If you let me talk to him,
I could find out.

27:05.726 --> 27:08.629
‐ So, uh, what kind
of stuff do you paint?

27:08.662 --> 27:12.165
‐ Um, I have been
experimenting with landscapes.

27:12.199 --> 27:14.001
I found this beautiful spot.

27:14.034 --> 27:16.136
And I photograph
the ocean from there

27:16.170 --> 27:17.404
all throughout the day,

27:17.437 --> 27:20.674
as a reference.
‐ [muffled conversation]

27:20.707 --> 27:23.477
‐ Yeah, the water is
incredibly peaceful.

27:23.510 --> 27:26.013
‐ Yeah, until it's not.

27:26.046 --> 27:27.548
Anytime you're out
on open water,

27:27.581 --> 27:30.017
you're minutes away
from a slap in the face.

27:30.050 --> 27:31.618
‐ So do you still
work the boats?

27:31.652 --> 27:32.452
‐ Oh, no.

27:32.486 --> 27:36.456
I had a stroke
a couple of years ago,

27:36.490 --> 27:39.359
and my boys decided
that it was enough.

27:39.393 --> 27:41.728
They grounded me.

27:47.534 --> 27:50.270
‐ The Lam kid
fucking cut our traps.

27:50.304 --> 27:52.639
The whole fleet
in Dutchman's Cove.

27:52.673 --> 27:54.708
Keyser saw him screwing around
out there in his whaler,

27:54.741 --> 27:56.410
called it in.

27:56.443 --> 27:59.146
‐ The gall
of that goddamn family.

27:59.179 --> 28:01.515
‐ You think it's CJ Lam?

28:01.548 --> 28:02.516
‐ Yeah.

28:02.549 --> 28:04.251
‐ That's a couple thousand
dollars we're out,

28:04.284 --> 28:07.020
plus all the lost time
resetting those lines.

28:07.054 --> 28:09.156
‐ But I'm not doing it.

28:09.189 --> 28:11.558
I mean it.

28:11.592 --> 28:13.160
I told you something like this
was gonna happen.

28:13.193 --> 28:14.595
‐ Shut up, Sean.

28:16.763 --> 28:20.667
‐ You said you wanted to ask
some questions about Percy?

28:20.701 --> 28:25.405
‐ I‐‐I realize this
can be sensitive.

28:25.439 --> 28:28.008
I'm just covering
all the bases.

28:28.041 --> 28:30.143
‐ What do you wanna know?

28:30.177 --> 28:31.445
‐ Any possibility that

28:31.478 --> 28:35.249
Percy might have been
involved with drugs?

28:35.282 --> 28:38.752
‐ Well, I mean, sure.

28:38.785 --> 28:41.121
She could have tried it
here and there.

28:41.154 --> 28:42.556
All kids do.

28:42.589 --> 28:44.191
‐ Well, if she dealt
with certain people

28:44.224 --> 28:45.292
and she had some cash,

28:45.325 --> 28:47.227
could she have been trying

28:47.261 --> 28:49.630
to find something lucrative?

28:49.663 --> 28:52.366
‐ And that's
your working theory?

28:52.399 --> 28:55.402
That Percy was
the island's El Chapo?

28:55.435 --> 28:57.137
Trust me, I'd have seen
that if it was coming.

28:57.171 --> 28:58.505
‐ What makes you so sure?

28:58.539 --> 29:00.407
‐ 18 months, 12 days sober.
That's what.

29:00.440 --> 29:01.608
I'd have sniffed it out.

29:01.642 --> 29:03.710
‐ You sure it's not 11 days?
‐ Fuck off.

29:03.744 --> 29:05.612
‐ I think it's 11 days.

29:05.646 --> 29:07.381
‐ You know what?
It was late that night

29:07.414 --> 29:09.149
when Percy's car
broke down,

29:09.183 --> 29:12.553
but she was heading somewhere.

29:12.586 --> 29:15.455
Could she have been trying
to get off the island?

29:15.489 --> 29:16.290
‐ Sure.

29:16.323 --> 29:19.493
‐ Any idea where
she might've been going?

29:19.526 --> 29:22.629
‐ If I did, I would've
mentioned it already.

29:22.663 --> 29:27.367
‐ It's just that...

29:27.401 --> 29:30.370
I spoke with Risa today.

29:30.404 --> 29:33.507
[tense music]

29:33.540 --> 29:38.011
She was pretty shaken up about
her daughter being missing.

29:38.045 --> 29:39.613
‐ When?

29:39.646 --> 29:42.783
‐ This afternoon.

29:42.816 --> 29:46.420
‐ I don't understand why
you're bothering talking to her

29:46.453 --> 29:49.323
at a time like this.

29:49.356 --> 29:52.159
‐ She's her mother.
She said Percy came to her‐‐

29:52.192 --> 29:53.627
this would've been about
nine months ago‐‐

29:53.660 --> 29:57.064
because she was frightened
about some things.

29:57.097 --> 29:59.566
‐ Risa likes to exaggerate.

29:59.600 --> 30:02.336
I wouldn't take much stock
in what she has to say.

30:02.369 --> 30:03.770
[chair scrapes]

30:03.804 --> 30:05.672
‐ Oh, sorry.

30:05.706 --> 30:10.477
Meg, have you ever thought
about living on the mainland?

30:10.511 --> 30:12.012
I guess that it's‐‐
it's a big adjustment

30:12.045 --> 30:13.247
if you've grown up here.

30:13.280 --> 30:15.749
‐ I also talked to Caroline.

30:15.782 --> 30:17.284
‐ And who's Caroline?

30:17.317 --> 30:19.520
‐ Percy's roommate
on the mainland.

30:19.553 --> 30:23.423
‐ Oh, that girl.
I forgot her name.

30:23.457 --> 30:25.158
‐ Well, she seems to think
that Percy was trying

30:25.192 --> 30:26.760
to get away from something.

30:26.793 --> 30:31.198
She was always on edge,
and then eventually,

30:31.231 --> 30:34.134
she just couldn't handle it.

30:34.168 --> 30:35.335
‐ Couldn't handle what?

30:35.369 --> 30:38.372
‐ She had
an emotional breakdown.

30:38.405 --> 30:41.708
She left the apartment
and disappeared.

30:41.742 --> 30:46.180
‐ Is that true?
‐ No, Percy was fine.

30:46.213 --> 30:49.116
She decided the mainland
wasn't for her.

30:49.149 --> 30:51.018
She wanted
to be with her family,

30:51.051 --> 30:53.353
so I got her home.

30:53.387 --> 30:55.022
‐ You said
she came back on her own.

30:55.055 --> 30:56.156
‐ She did.
We just helped her.

30:56.190 --> 30:58.492
‐ You went too.

30:58.525 --> 31:02.729
Are you fucking serious?
‐ Bro, just‐‐

31:02.763 --> 31:03.630
‐ You lied to me.

31:03.664 --> 31:07.100
‐ We would've brought you
if you wouldn't‐‐

31:07.134 --> 31:08.468
let it go.

31:08.502 --> 31:11.538
‐ What is this,
"the mainland wasn't for her?"

31:11.572 --> 31:14.007
She was really scared
that somebody was after her.

31:14.041 --> 31:16.210
Some guy.
‐ Percy said this?

31:16.243 --> 31:18.245
‐ Yeah, said she started to
lock herself in the apartment

31:18.278 --> 31:19.413
and not come out.

31:19.446 --> 31:21.748
‐ This roommate is
so full of shit.

31:21.782 --> 31:24.518
‐ Ma, you said she was fine.

31:24.551 --> 31:25.352
‐ She was.

31:25.385 --> 31:27.154
‐ You know
what I find surprising?

31:27.187 --> 31:28.488
Your mother never mentioned
this

31:28.522 --> 31:30.757
when we were looking all around
trying to find where Percy was.

31:30.791 --> 31:33.260
‐ Harry...
‐ What is your fucking problem?

31:33.293 --> 31:35.229
What exactly are
you accusing her of?

31:35.262 --> 31:37.331
‐ Something happened
over there.

31:37.364 --> 31:39.299
I'd just like to understand

31:39.333 --> 31:41.001
why she left the island
so suddenly,

31:41.034 --> 31:44.471
and when she came back,
she was in worse shape.

31:44.505 --> 31:46.573
‐ So you think
we did something?

31:46.607 --> 31:49.176
Tore her outta there
against her will?

31:49.209 --> 31:52.646
‐ There had been a fight, and
the room was all smashed up.

31:52.679 --> 31:55.215
So can you tell me
something about that?

31:55.249 --> 31:56.783
Any of you, can you?

31:56.817 --> 31:59.186
‐ Percy wanted to come home.

31:59.219 --> 32:02.489
She called on me, and I went
with Colin to pick her up.

32:02.523 --> 32:05.192
That's what happened,
and I'm not gonna entertain

32:05.225 --> 32:06.593
some bullshit version of events

32:06.627 --> 32:11.131
from a stranger
Percy met on Craigslist.

32:11.164 --> 32:12.566
‐ Why didn't you tell me
any of this?

32:12.599 --> 32:13.700
‐ Sean, shut up.

32:13.734 --> 32:16.270
‐ She's my daughter.
You two it‐‐

32:16.303 --> 32:18.605
‐ Don't start with that.
You know what you did.

32:18.639 --> 32:20.541
‐ No, no, no. It's always
like this with you guys.

32:20.574 --> 32:22.009
Squeezing me out.
This is about my‐‐

32:22.042 --> 32:24.178
‐ You were passed out
in the fucking woods.

32:24.211 --> 32:26.280
We're cleaning up your shit.

32:26.313 --> 32:28.649
If life were fair,
you'd be paying us alimony.

32:28.682 --> 32:32.019
[tense music]

32:32.052 --> 32:33.687
‐ Fuck!

32:33.720 --> 32:40.394
♪ ♪

32:41.662 --> 32:45.465
‐ Well, that
about wraps up dinner.

33:09.590 --> 33:11.491
‐ I can't leave. ‐ Harry, this family
is suffering.

33:11.525 --> 33:14.228
We shouldn't be here.

33:14.261 --> 33:17.130
‐ You go ahead.

33:17.164 --> 33:21.335
‐ What is going on with you?

33:21.368 --> 33:23.036
‐ Thanks for coming by.

33:23.070 --> 33:25.439
‐ Oh, we just overstayed
our welcome,

33:25.472 --> 33:27.407
but thank you
for a delicious dinner.

33:27.441 --> 33:32.179
‐ Drive safe.

33:32.212 --> 33:34.481
Aren't you going
with your girlfriend?

33:41.588 --> 33:45.092
‐ You went to
that construction site today.

33:45.125 --> 33:48.428
‐ Ah. so there it is.

33:48.462 --> 33:50.364
You spent the morning
stalking me

33:50.397 --> 33:52.432
instead of looking for Percy.

33:52.799 --> 33:55.702
‐ The guy that you talked with
by the trailer.

33:55.736 --> 33:57.504
‐ He's an old friend
of my husband's

33:57.538 --> 34:00.174
who's been kind enough
to give me a loan

34:00.207 --> 34:03.510
because I can't get one
from any bank around.

34:03.544 --> 34:05.379
I had to borrow
against this house

34:05.412 --> 34:07.514
and sell off
a bunch of equipment,

34:07.548 --> 34:10.484
which lowered our count.
But we had no choice.

34:10.517 --> 34:14.188
You have any idea how hard it
is to turn a profit lobstering?

34:14.221 --> 34:16.557
‐ I can believe it,

34:16.590 --> 34:22.162
but some of the things you say,
I don't know.

34:22.196 --> 34:24.231
‐ What?
‐ Risa.

34:24.264 --> 34:25.766
‐ Risa?

34:25.799 --> 34:27.601
I went to talk to her
for information,

34:27.634 --> 34:29.169
just the way you did.

34:29.203 --> 34:33.340
‐ Percy ran away from home.
Why'd she do that?

34:33.373 --> 34:35.042
‐ What, you think
because of me?

34:35.075 --> 34:37.077
What kind of a person
do you think I am?

34:37.110 --> 34:38.679
‐ Well, you're the kind
of person who would say

34:38.712 --> 34:41.081
the last time you saw Percy
was when she left work.

34:41.114 --> 34:44.017
‐ Yeah, what about it?
‐ That gash on her forehead?

34:44.051 --> 34:46.086
You said you saw it
with your own eyes?

34:46.119 --> 34:47.054
How?

34:47.087 --> 34:49.356
She got a couple of hours
after she left work.

34:49.389 --> 34:50.691
You lied to me.

34:51.792 --> 34:56.363
She came to you,
later that night,

34:56.396 --> 34:59.066
didn't she?
‐ Fucking...

34:59.099 --> 35:02.169
She's still part of the family!
[clattering]

35:02.202 --> 35:05.072
‐ Hey, you guys stop it.

35:05.105 --> 35:06.507
Sean.
Hey.

35:06.540 --> 35:09.743
Sean, stop it.

35:09.776 --> 35:12.079
‐ Are you done?

35:18.318 --> 35:19.620
‐ You know,

35:19.653 --> 35:22.422
if you're investigating anyone,
it should be him.

35:22.456 --> 35:24.491
‐ What the hell is the matter
with you?

35:24.525 --> 35:27.094
‐ Walk it off.

35:27.127 --> 35:30.564
‐ Fuck you.

35:30.597 --> 35:33.467
‐ Are you gonna be all right?

35:33.500 --> 35:36.970
‐ You need to leave right now.
Just go.

35:39.139 --> 35:42.075
[ominous music]

35:42.109 --> 35:47.314
♪ ♪

35:47.347 --> 35:49.349
‐ [crying]

35:49.383 --> 35:55.756
‐ Percy, what happened?
Who did this?

35:55.789 --> 35:59.760
‐ Take me home.
Please?

35:59.793 --> 36:03.230
‐ Of course.
Go to sleep, baby girl.

36:03.263 --> 36:06.200
♪ ♪

36:06.233 --> 36:10.003
Of course I'll take you home.

36:10.037 --> 36:11.471
It's all right.

36:11.505 --> 36:18.579
♪ ♪

36:23.116 --> 36:24.418
You tired?

36:24.451 --> 36:30.757
♪ ♪

36:30.791 --> 36:33.794
Sleep.

36:33.827 --> 36:35.796
I'll be back.

36:35.829 --> 36:42.703
♪ ♪

36:51.411 --> 36:57.484
‐ Leave me alone.
Leave me alone.

36:57.518 --> 37:01.021
[whispering] Go away.

37:01.054 --> 37:03.290
Please go away.

37:03.323 --> 37:06.059
Leave me alone.

37:19.039 --> 37:21.542
‐ I'm sorry.

37:21.575 --> 37:25.078
‐ I have never seen you
behave that way.

37:25.112 --> 37:27.581
Pushing them like that.

37:27.614 --> 37:31.485
‐ That's being direct.
Isn't that a good thing?

37:31.518 --> 37:37.624
‐ No, you were being mean
and out of control.

37:37.658 --> 37:42.095
That family is in pain.
They're mourning a loss.

37:42.129 --> 37:47.467
‐ I'm not so sure about that.
‐ Ugh, come on, Harry.

37:47.501 --> 37:50.671
You can't assume just because
of your childhood

37:50.704 --> 37:53.373
that every family is cruel.

37:53.407 --> 37:56.577
‐ I had good reasons
to do what I did.

37:56.610 --> 38:00.147
‐ Well, I think you could
have done it differently.

38:00.180 --> 38:03.183
You didn't have
to drag me into it.

38:03.217 --> 38:07.087
‐ You're right.
I'm better on my own.

38:07.120 --> 38:10.057
[melancholy music]

38:11.658 --> 38:13.493
‐ You asked me what I thought.

38:14.261 --> 38:18.665
I think this case is bringing
out a really ugly side of you.

38:43.290 --> 38:50.197
[ambient music] ♪ ♪

39:14.655 --> 39:18.425
‐ Hey.
‐ Hey, look, Sonya is sleeping,

39:18.458 --> 39:22.596
so can we...?

39:26.800 --> 39:29.002
‐ There's something
I have to tell you.

39:30.637 --> 39:32.639
‐ You wanna sit down?

39:38.178 --> 39:45.052
‐ So... we lied

39:45.085 --> 39:48.589
about not having seen
Percy that night.

39:48.622 --> 39:50.791
‐ Yeah, I know.

39:50.824 --> 39:52.593
‐ My mom and I did see her.

39:52.626 --> 39:55.596
And the reason we said
we didn't

39:55.629 --> 40:01.735
is because of me.

40:01.768 --> 40:07.140
Percy was confronting me
about some stuff.

40:07.174 --> 40:11.578
‐ Some stuff? You're talking
about your drug use, right?

40:16.083 --> 40:18.018
‐ Yeah.

40:18.051 --> 40:19.586
It started with painkillers.

40:21.555 --> 40:25.158
I screwed up my shoulder
on the boats.

40:25.192 --> 40:29.763
But‐‐yeah.

40:32.399 --> 40:35.369
I'm dealing with it.

40:35.402 --> 40:37.337
But that night,

40:37.371 --> 40:41.341
Percy was upset with me,

40:41.375 --> 40:45.145
and I did make things worse,

40:45.179 --> 40:47.147
and I needed to fix that.

40:47.181 --> 40:52.753
And I didn't‐‐I didn't want
anyone to recognize my car.

40:54.421 --> 40:58.725
‐ So you are the one who was
driving Percy's car

40:58.759 --> 41:03.363
towards Diez's place?
It wasn't Percy?

41:03.397 --> 41:06.200
[somber music]

41:06.233 --> 41:09.002
♪ ♪

41:09.036 --> 41:12.506
That man that was
stalking Percy.

41:12.539 --> 41:16.510
You think it was Colin, right?

41:16.543 --> 41:19.646
‐ What?
What makes you ask that?

41:19.680 --> 41:22.449
‐ You told me to look into him,
right, so...

41:23.550 --> 41:25.419
‐ I was just pissed off.

41:25.452 --> 41:30.457
I mean, Colin's always the
good guy and I'm the fuck‐up.

41:30.490 --> 41:33.760
That's the way my mom sees it.

41:33.794 --> 41:37.130
It‐‐it makes her blind
to everything else.

41:39.233 --> 41:42.469
‐ Like what?

41:42.503 --> 41:45.706
‐ Colin and Percy
were always close.

41:49.710 --> 41:51.712
‐ What do you mean by that?

41:55.649 --> 42:00.587
‐ I don't know,
I should get going.

42:00.621 --> 42:05.726
‐ Sean, did Meg send you?

42:10.230 --> 42:12.499
‐ I'm just trying
to be a good son.

42:26.580 --> 42:29.516
[eerie music]

42:29.550 --> 42:36.623
♪ ♪

42:45.299 --> 42:49.636
‐ You can see how I might have
just needed an escape.

42:53.640 --> 42:57.311
It just gets worse,
doesn't it?

42:57.344 --> 43:00.280
The more you learn.

43:04.318 --> 43:10.657
‐ Maybe you're just actually
on a beach somewhere

43:10.691 --> 43:12.459
where no one can get to you.

43:16.563 --> 43:21.502
‐ Running never solves
anything.

43:21.535 --> 43:23.570
For you especially.

43:39.419 --> 43:41.755
‐ Do you feel that?
‐ Yeah, my boots are sticking.

43:41.788 --> 43:44.057
‐ We call it gumbo mud.

43:44.758 --> 43:50.631
That's how you know
there's good oysters around.

43:50.664 --> 43:53.734
‐ Look at you.
You're a genius.

44:00.174 --> 44:03.143
[eerie music]

44:03.177 --> 44:10.184
♪ ♪
